Here's a complete example of an MCP server wrapping a REST API with `HttpClient`.

## Tool Class — `ApiTools.cs`

```csharp
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;

[McpServerToolType]
public class ApiTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<ApiTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Get a user by their ID.")]
    public async Task<string> GetUser(
        [Description("The numeric user ID")] int userId,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching user {UserId}", userId);
        var json = await httpClient.GetStringAsync($"/users/{userId}", cancellationToken);
        return json;
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("Search users by name. Returns matching results.")]
    public async Task<string> SearchUsers(
        [Description("Name or partial name to search for")] string query,
        [Description("Max results to return (1-50)")] int limit = 10,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Searching users: {Query}", query);
        var response = await httpClient.GetAsync(
            $"/users?q={Uri.EscapeDataString(query)}&limit={limit}", cancellationToken);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
    }

    [McpServerTool(Destructive = false, ReadOnly = true),
     Description("List all available API resource categories.")]
    public async Task<string> ListCategories(CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        return await httpClient.GetStringAsync("/categories", cancellationToken);
    }
}
```

## Program.cs — stdio transport

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: log to stderr only — stdout is the JSON-RPC transport
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

builder.Services.AddHttpClient<ApiTools>(client =>
{
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.example.com");
    client.DefaultRequestHeaders.Add("Accept", "application/json");
});

builder.Services.AddMcpServer(options =>
{
    options.ServerInfo = new() { Name = "ApiMcpServer", Version = "1.0.0" };
})
.WithStdioServerTransport()
.WithToolsFromAssembly();

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

## How DI Works for MCP Tools

The SDK supports **two injection styles**:

| Style | Class type | How services arrive |
|---|---|---|
| **Constructor injection** | Non-static class | Services in the constructor (shown above) |
| **Method parameter injection** | Static class | DI services as method params alongside tool params |

**Key behavior:** The SDK inspects each parameter's type. Known framework types (`CancellationToken`, `IMcpServer`, `IProgress<>`) and any type registered in DI are **injected automatically** and **hidden from the tool schema**. Only parameters with `[Description]` are exposed to the LLM.

So in the `GetUser` example above:
- `httpClient` and `logger` → injected via constructor, invisible to the LLM
- `userId` → exposed in the tool schema with its description
- `cancellationToken` → injected by the framework

This means you can freely add services like `IConfiguration`, `IMemoryCache`, or your own interfaces — the LLM never sees them.

### To scaffold this project from scratch:

```bash
dotnet new mcpserver -n ApiMcpServer
cd ApiMcpServer
```

Then replace the generated `Tools.cs` and `Program.cs` with the code above.
